Source: OIE Disease Information 2006; 19(49) [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/A_CURRENT.HTM#Sec9>

Newcastle disease in Serbia and Montenegro
------------------------------------------
An outbreak of Newcastle disease in Serbia and Montenegro was last reported
to the OIE (Office International des Epizooties) in February 2002.
This report is of information received on (and dated) 5 Dec 2006 from Dr
Dejan Krnjaic, chief veterinary officer, Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry
and Water Management, Belgrade:
Reason for immediate notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease or
infection in a country or zone/compartment following a report declaring the
outbreak(s) ended.
Identification of agent: Newcastle disease virus.
Date of start of the event: 27 Nov 2006.
Clinical disease: yes.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, postmortem, and laboratory.
Details of outbreaks: 2 outbreaks in villages located at Srbija province at
Srednje (27 Nov 2006) and Belgrade (29 Nov 2006) are reported. In the 1st
outbreak at Srednje, there were 3672 susceptible birds, including 748 cases
and deaths, with the remaining chickens being destroyed. In the 2nd
outbreak at Belgrade, there were 225 susceptible birds, all were cases and
died.
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/http://www.oie.int/cartes/19_49_YUG.bmp>
Description of affected population: backyard poultry.
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed: Veterinary Specialized
Institute "Kraljevo"
Results: hemagglutination inhibition test and virus isolation were positive
on 4 Dec 2006 and 5 Dec 2006, respectively.
Source of outbreaks or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive.
Control measures undertaken:
stamping out in Zitiste village on 4 Dec 2006;
quarantine;
movement control inside the country;
screening;
zoning (a protection zone with a radius of at least 3 km and a surveillance
zone with a radius of at least 10 km around the outbreaks);
vaccination;
disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s);
dipping/spraying.
Ongoing vaccination in response to the outbreaks: in Srbija, 5089 birds
have been vaccinated.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to OIE reports, a wide variety of hosts for outbreaks have
occurred in the last 18 months in this general geographic region.
Bulgaria's outbreak was in backyard poultry; Cyprus included poultry and
ostriches; Greece had commercial layer poultry affected; Macedonia included
backyard poultry; Romania's outbreak was in commercial layers imported from
France, and Slovakia's outbreak occurred in pigeons and turtledoves. - Mod.PC]
